  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's occupation of Kuwait reflects his need to escape from economic and social problems arising from the eight-year war with Iran.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Saddam says he fought the war to protect Sunni Arabs from the fundamentalist Shiite Persian revolution in Iran
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   and should not be expected to repay war debts to fellow Sunni Arabs.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   By focusing on claimed misdeeds of Kuwait he hopes to divert attention from the economic and social chaos reigning at home
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   while gaining the wealth and territory represented by Kuwait.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   This is the first time that an Arab state has deposed the government of a fellow Arab League member.
  </a>
